data.name: lblOreEmphasisDescription.Text
data.value: Setting this will result in a yellow glow to be placed behind ore, and a purple glow behind gems. When scaling images down, for example to use them as small preview image of a map, this looks pretty good.

data.name: cbReplacePreview.ToolTip
data.value: FinalAlert2 previews generally look quite poor. Replacing them with a downscaled version of the resulting image often looks much better, which is what this option does. DANGEROUS: comments and ini formatting is lost. The original map is overwritten!

data.name: rbAutoFilename.ToolTip
data.value: Automatic filename resolution uses a CSF, missions.ini or [Basic]/Name if possible. This scheme works well for determining the name of TS/RA2 multiplayer maps as well as campaign missions. When deduced from missions.pkt or missions.ini they are localized in the the language of the installed game.

data.name: cbPreserveThumbAspect.ToolTip
data.value: Generate a thumbnail of specified size. Format is in "width,height". If you specify 0 either for width or height, aspect ratio is preserved while the width/height is maximized for the non-zero component.

data.name: cbOutputThumbnail.ToolTip
data.value: Generate a thumbnail of specified size. Format is in (width,height). If you specify 0 either for width or height, aspect ratio is preserved while the width/height is maximized for the non-zero component.

data.name: rbEngineAuto.ToolTip
data.value: Tries to automatically deduce whether your map is made for RA2/YR, but is often unsuccessful, since this information is not actually stored in the map. This will never render the map as if it is a TS/FS map, if it is you need to manually select this!

data.name: lblBatchDesc.Text
data.value: Batch rendering can be used to process multiple maps of the same game/mod with the same settings. First configure the desired settings on "Main settings" and "Misc settings" tabs and then add the needed maps either by the "Add maps" button or drag and drop the files in the field below. Finally, press the "Start batch processing" button.
